<br>
But NEVER send your newb pet on something strong, which you can't kill, or if the pet is melee, the big critter will attack whoever is in front of them, even peaceful critters that have nothing to do with the attack <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000028><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub60.ezboard.com/bcreaturehandlersofswg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=muerrte>Muerrte</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 22<br> <font color=#70DB93>(8/23/03 12:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub60.ezboard.com/fcreaturehandlersofswgfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Climbing up the Ch tree</span><hr size=1> Those are some good ideas, but feeding your pet does not make them regen faster, it only makes their health and action wounds go away no matter how high they are.  As for climbing the tree here is my suggestion, and the best way IMHO.<br>
<br>
1- Get Taming I and Training I<br>
<br>
2- Completely forget about empathy for now<br>
<br>
3- After you have Taming I and Training I, go straight to management III.  The reason being so you can have 2 pets out at once, go grab 2 low lvl pets (good idea being around lvl 10 or so) then find an area with a lot of lowbie creatures and sit out there for hours if you can deal with boredom.  On some nights i was able to pull in over 200k CH exp a night =)<br>
<br>
